# Rental Property API

A RESTful API built with Java Spring Boot to manage rental properties.
The API allows users to register, login, and manage rental listings.
It uses PostgreSQL for data storage and is containerized with Docker.

## Technologies

- Java 21
- Spring Boot
- Spring Data JPA
- PostgreSQL
- Docker & Docker Compose
- Render (API deployment)
- Neon (PostgreSQL hosting)

## Project Architecture

- Controller layer: handles HTTP requests
- Service layer: contains business logic
- Repository layer: handles database access
- PostgreSQL database hosted on Neon
- Application packaged and run using Docker

## Environment Variables

The following environment variables are required:

- DB_URL=jdbc:postgresql://<host>:5432/<database>
- DB_USERNAME=your_db_username
- DB_PASSWORD=your_db_password
- SERVER_PORT=8080

## Run Locally with Docker

1. Clone the repository
   git clone https://github.com/your-username/rental-property-api.git

2. Move into the project directory
   cd rental-property-api

3. Create a `.env` file with the required environment variables

4. Start the project using Docker Compose
   docker compose up --build

5. The API will be available at
   http://localhost:8080

## API Base URLs

- Local: http://localhost:8080/api
- Production: https://your-project-name.onrender.com/api

## API Endpoints

### Register User
POST /auth/register

Request Body:
{
  "email": "user@example.com",
  "password": "password123"
}

Response:
201 Created

### Login
POST /auth/login

Response:
200 OK
Returns JWT token

### Create Property
POST /properties

Headers:
Authorization: Bearer <token>

Response:
201 Created

## Deployment

- The API is deployed on Render using Docker
- PostgreSQL database is hosted on Neon
- Docker image is built automatically on deploy

## Docker

- Dockerfile is used to build the Spring Boot application
- Docker Compose is used to manage services
- Application runs inside a container

